The object for this example is to show that you can capture pretty much
anything that you can do in a terminal session.

The ability to capture an editing session is useful, as it is difficult
to describe what you type in an editor without showing it. Scripting a
vi, vim or emacs session would be highly annoying. You would be better 
off providing sed and awk examples.

It is still fascinating to watch a playback in a screen rather than as
a movie file. It might just be a series of escape codes and characters,
but it looks great. Of course, all of your typos and idiosyncrasies show
up in the output. 

Highlighting and pasting with the mouse does not show up, just the results.

For example, typing a line and duplicating it from the keyboard and then
highlighting and copying and pasting with the mouse look the same.
